docs.lead_paragraph: Union-backed groups are pressuring a handful of renegade House Democrats from New York and New Jersey to back the party's efforts to overhaul the health care system. The organizations -- including the Communications Workers of America and the Working Families Party -- say they are disappointed that these lawmakers voted against the bill approved by the House this month and left open the possibility that they could withhold political support from them or even actively oppose them in next year's elections unless they back final legislation.

headline.main: Region's House Democrats Facing Pressure on Health Care Overhaul

docs.abstract: Union-backed organizations pressure some House Democrats from New York State and New Jersey to back party's efforts to overhaul health care system; say they are disappointed that these lawmakers voted against bill approved by House and warn that they could withhold political support from them; warnings come as Democrats across country are concerned that their party's candidates will face hostile electoral climate in 2010 (M)
docs.snippet: Union-backed groups say they may withhold support or even oppose lawmakers who do not support health care legislation.

docs.lead_paragraph: Anxious that Saturday's party-line Senate vote to open debate on a health care overhaul gives them little maneuvering room, Obama administration officials and their Congressional allies are stepping up overtures to select Senate Republicans in hopes of winning their ultimate support. The two moderate Republican senators from Maine, Susan Collins and Olympia J. Snowe, say Senator Harry Reid, the majority leader, reached out to them after he unveiled the Senate measure, encouraging them to bring forward their ideas and concerns.

headline.main: Democrats Step Up Push for Votes on Health Care

docs.abstract: Obama administration officials and Congressional allies step up overtures to select Senate Republicans in hopes of winning their support on health care overhaul; both sides, after party-line vote to move to full health care debate, are acutely aware of wavering in their ranks; moderate Republican Senators Susan Collins and Olympia Snowe of Maine and handful of swing senators from both parties have become center of attention; photos (M)
